I'm proud to introduce a bill that will help those who find themselves in an emergency situation by enhancing the centers within the National Poison Data System that offer free, confidential, expert medical advice 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. >> https://t.co/ME2oBle58y

Poison control centers save countless lives, prevent toxic exposure & poisoning injury, and reduce billions of dollars in unnecessary #healthcare costs. The data poison centers collect can even be used to identify hotspots for opioid misuse & overdose.
In one month alone, there were 9,039 #opioid exposures reported to poison control centers nationwide.

Since 2011, poison control centers have been working #behindthescenes to fight against the #opioidepidemic & have handled about 500,000 cases of opioid misuse & abuse – that’s approximately 192 cases per day, every day.

This week, I joined @RepEliotEngel @RepJoeBarton & @RepDianaDeGette to introduce H.R.5329, the Poison Center Network Enhancement Act. This #bipartisan bill reauthorizes funding for the poison control center's toll-free number >> https://t.co/ME2oBle58y

Heartbreaking statistic: According to the @CDCgov, opioids killed more than 42,000 people in 2016, more than any year on record.
Last year, @POTUS declared the #opioidcrisis a nationwide public health emergency and earlier this month, the President extended that designation. https://t.co/U3kimitLFy
@POTUS has prioritized combating the opioid and heroin epidemic with the establishment of his Commission on Combating Drug Addiction and the Opioid Crisis >> https://t.co/Ya7rR2LEut

The Task Force unites members of the medical community, to members of the #education and #lawenforcement communities, in order to discuss and implement best practices to combat the #opioidepidemic on all fronts.

Due to Ann Vermilion’s leadership in the Task Force as well as work of the medical professionals in Grant County, written prescriptions for opioid medications have significantly declined in Grant County.

Grant County’s Opioid and Substance Abuse Task Force, which has been in existence since 2014, is working hard to put an end to the devastating #opioid and heroin epidemic that is taking the lives of too many Hoosiers.
Indiana is 1 of 4 states where the drug overdose mortality rate has quadrupled since 1999. In 2015, there were 529 drug overdose deaths involving an opioid in the #Hoosier state alone.
